claim.claim-text:
11. A computer-implemented method of assuring separation of aircraft between a first aircraft and other aircraft, comprising: 
determining whether the other aircraft are transmitting tracking information, wherein such aircraft transmitting the tracking information are armed aircraft, further wherein the tracking information comprises position and velocity, still further wherein the position is defined in a geographic coordinate system; 
obtaining the tracking information from each armed aircraft; 
applying separation assurance algorithms to the tracking information for each armed aircraft within a predetermined zone relative to the first aircraft; and 
alerting an observer when the separation assurance algorithms are indicative of a threat to the first aircraft.

17. A machine-readable medium having instructions stored thereon capable of causing a processor to carry out a method of assuring separation of aircraft between a first aircraft and other aircraft, the method comprising: 
determining whether the other aircraft are transmitting tracking information, wherein such aircraft transmitting the tracking information are armed aircraft, further wherein the tracking information comprises position and velocity, still further wherein the position is defined in a geographic coordinate system; 
obtaining the tracking information from each armed aircraft; 
applying separation assurance algorithms to the tracking information for each armed aircraft within a predetermined zone relative to the first aircraft; and 
alerting an observer when the separation assurance algorithms are indicative of a threat to the first aircraft.

22. An alerting system for a first aircraft on approach to a first runway of a pair of parallel runways, the system comprising: 
at least one track file element, wherein each at least one track file element corresponds to an individual other aircraft, further wherein each at least one track file element comprises data, the data comprising: 
latitude data, wherein the latitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; 
longitude data, wherein the longitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; and 
altitude data, wherein the altitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; 

wherein the alerting system generates alerts to an observer on the first aircraft when the data are indicative of a threat to the observer from at least one other aircraft, wherein each at least one other aircraft is within a predetermined zone relative to the first aircraft, further wherein each at least one other aircraft is on an approach to a second runway of the pair of parallel runways.

24. A method of assuring separation between a first aircraft and other aircraft, wherein the first aircraft is on an approach to a first runway of a pair of parallel runways, the method comprising: 
determining which of the other aircraft are transmitting tracking information, wherein such other aircraft transmitting tracking information are armed aircraft and the remaining other aircraft are unarmed aircraft; 
assuring separation between the first aircraft and other aircraft using an alternate alerting method when the other aircraft are unarmed aircraft; 
assuring separation between the first aircraft and other aircraft using the alternate alerting method when the other aircraft are outside a predetermined zone relative to the first aircraft; 
alerting an observer in the first aircraft in response to the tracking information when the tracking information indicates that at least one of the armed aircraft is a threat to the first aircraft, wherein alerting an observer in response to the tracking information occurs only when the at least one armed aircraft is within the predetermined zone.

25. The method of claim 24, wherein the tracking information comprises: 
latitude data, wherein the latitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; 
longitude data, wherein the longitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; and 
altitude data, wherein the altitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system;

26. The method of claim 25, wherein the tracking information further comprises: 
universal coordinate time data; 
velocity data; 
approach data; and 
alerting system mode data.

30. A machine-readable medium having instructions stored thereon capable of causing a processor to carry out a method of assuring separation between a first aircraft and other aircraft, wherein the first aircraft is on an approach to a first runway of a pair of parallel runways, the method comprising: 
determining which of the other aircraft are transmitting tracking information, wherein such other aircraft transmitting tracking information are armed aircraft and the remaining other aircraft are unarmed aircraft; 
assuring separation between the first aircraft and other aircraft using an alternate alerting method when the other aircraft are unarmed aircraft; 
assuring separation between the first aircraft and other aircraft using the alternate alerting method when the other aircraft are outside a predetermined zone relative to the first aircraft; 
alerting an observer in the first aircraft in response to the tracking information when the tracking information indicates that at least one of the armed aircraft is a threat to the first aircraft, wherein alerting an observer in response to the tracking information occurs only when the at least one armed aircraft is within the predetermined zone.

31. An alerting system, comprising: 
a processor; and 
a machine-readable medium coupled to the processor, wherein the machine-readable medium has instructions stored thereon capable of causing the processor to carry out a method of assuring separation between a first aircraft and other aircraft, wherein the first aircraft is on an approach to a first runway of a pair of parallel runways, further wherein the method comprises: 
determining which of the other aircraft are transmitting tracking information, wherein such other aircraft transmitting tracking information are armed aircraft and the remaining other aircraft are unarmed aircraft; 
assuring separation between the first aircraft and other aircraft using an alternate alerting method when the other aircraft are unarmed aircraft; 
assuring separation between the first aircraft and other aircraft using the alternate alerting method when the other aircraft are outside a predetermined zone relative to the first aircraft; 
alerting an observer in the first aircraft in response to the tracking information when the tracking information indicates that at least one of the armed aircraft is a threat to the first aircraft, wherein alerting an observer in response to the tracking information occurs only when the at least one armed aircraft is within the predetermined zone.

32. The alerting system of claim 31, wherein the tracking information comprises: 
latitude data, wherein the latitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; 
longitude data, wherein the longitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system; and 
altitude data, wherein the altitude data is defined in a geographic coordinate system;

33. The alerting system of claim 32, wherein the tracking information further comprises: 
universal coordinate time data; 
velocity data; 
approach data; and 
alerting system mode data.
